# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hardware-in-the-loop
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] An **embedded system** is a specialized computer system—a combination of a computer processor, computer memory, and input/output peripheral devices—that has a dedicated function within a larger mechanical or electronic system.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] It is embedded as part of a complete device, often including electrical or electronic hardware and mechanical parts.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Embedded systems control many devices in common use.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In 2009, it was estimated that 98% of all microprocessors manufactured were used in embedded systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Because an embedded system typically controls physical operations of the machine that it is embedded within, it often has real-time computing constraints.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Modern embedded systems are often based on microcontrollers (i.e., microprocessors with integrated memory and peripheral interfaces), but ordinary microprocessors (using external chips for memory and peripheral interface circuits) are also common, especially in more complex systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In either case, the processor(s) used may be types ranging from general purpose to those specialized in a certain class of computations, or even custom designed for the application at hand.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] A common standard class of dedicated processors is the digital signal processor (DSP).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Since the embedded system is dedicated to specific tasks, design engineers can optimize it to reduce the size and cost of the product and increase its reliability and performance.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are mass-produced, benefiting from economies of scale.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Embedded systems range in size from portable personal devices such as digital watches and MP3 players to bigger machines like home appliances, industrial assembly lines, robots, transport vehicles, traffic light controllers, and medical imaging systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Often they constitute subsystems of other machines like avionics in aircraft and astrionics in spacecraft.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Large installations like factories, pipelines, and electrical grids rely on multiple embedded systems networked together.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Generalized through software customization, embedded systems such as programmable logic controllers frequently comprise their functional units.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The origins of the microprocessor and the microcontroller can be traced back to the MOS integrated circuit, which is an integrated circuit chip fabricated from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors) and was developed in the early 1960s.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] By 1964, MOS chips had reached higher transistor density and lower manufacturing costs than bipolar chips.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] MOS chips further increased in complexity at a rate predicted by Moore's law, leading to large-scale integration (LSI) with hundreds of transistors on a single MOS chip by the late 1960s.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The application of MOS LSI chips to computing was the basis for the first microprocessors, as engineers began recognizing that a complete computer processor system could be contained on several MOS LSI chips.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The first multi-chip microprocessors, the Four-Phase Systems AL1 in 1969 and the Garrett AiResearch MP944 in 1970, were developed with multiple MOS LSI chips.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The first single-chip microprocessor was the Intel 4004, released in 1971.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] It was developed by Federico Faggin, using his silicon-gate MOS technology, along with Intel engineers Marcian Hoff and Stan Mazor, and Busicom engineer Masatoshi Shima.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] One of the first recognizably modern embedded systems was the Apollo Guidance Computer, developed ca.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] 1965 by Charles Stark Draper at the MIT Instrumentation Laboratory.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] At the project's inception, the Apollo guidance computer was considered the riskiest item in the Apollo project as it employed the then newly developed monolithic integrated circuits to reduce the computer's size and weight.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] An early mass-produced embedded system was the Autonetics D-17 guidance computer for the Minuteman missile, released in 1961.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] When the Minuteman II went into production in 1966, the D-17 was replaced with a new computer that represented the first high-volume use of integrated circuits.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Since these early applications in the 1960s, embedded systems have come down in price and there has been a dramatic rise in processing power and functionality.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] An early microprocessor, the Intel 4004 (released in 1971), was designed for calculators and other small systems but still required external memory and support chips.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] By the early 1980s, memory, input and output system components had been integrated into the same chip as the processor, forming a microcontroller.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Microcontrollers find applications where a general-purpose computer would be too costly.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] As the cost of microprocessors and microcontrollers fell, the prevalence of embedded systems increased.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] A comparatively low-cost microcontroller may be programmed to fulfill the same role as a large number of separate components.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] With microcontrollers, it became feasible to replace, even in consumer products, expensive knob-based analog components such as potentiometers and variable capacitors with up/down buttons or knobs read out by a microprocessor.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Although in this context an embedded system is usually more complex than a traditional solution, most of the complexity is contained within the microcontroller itself.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Very few additional components may be needed and most of the design effort is in the software.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Software prototype and test can be quicker compared with the design and construction of a new circuit not using an embedded processor.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Embedded systems are commonly found in consumer, industrial, automotive, home appliances, medical, telecommunication, commercial, aerospace and military applications.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Telecommunications systems employ numerous embedded systems from telephone switches for the network to cell phones at the end user.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Computer networking uses dedicated routers and network bridges to route data.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Consumer electronics include MP3 players, television sets, mobile phones, video game consoles, digital cameras, GPS receivers, and printers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Household appliances, such as microwave ovens, washing machines and dishwashers, include embedded systems to provide flexibility, efficiency and features.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Advanced heating, ventilation, and air conditioning (HVAC) systems use networked thermostats to more accurately and efficiently control temperature that can change by time of day and season.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Home automation uses wired and wireless networking that can be used to control lights, climate, security, audio/visual, surveillance, etc., all of which use embedded devices for sensing and controlling.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Transportation systems from flight to automobiles increasingly use embedded systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] New airplanes contain advanced avionics such as inertial guidance systems and GPS receivers that also have considerable safety requirements.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Spacecraft rely on astrionics systems for trajectory correction.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Various electric motors — brushless DC motors, induction motors and DC motors — use electronic motor controllers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Automobiles, electric vehicles, and hybrid vehicles increasingly use embedded systems to maximize efficiency and reduce pollution.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Other automotive safety systems using embedded systems include anti-lock braking system (ABS), electronic stability control (ESC/ESP), traction control (TCS) and automatic four-wheel drive.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Medical equipment uses embedded systems for monitoring, and various medical imaging (positron emission tomography (PET), single-photon emission computed tomography (SPECT), computed tomography (CT), and magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) for non-invasive internal inspections.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Embedded systems within medical equipment are often powered by industrial computers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Embedded systems are used for safety-critical systems in aerospace and defense industries.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Unless connected to wired or wireless networks via on-chip 3G cellular or other methods for IoT monitoring and control purposes, these systems can be isolated from hacking and thus be more secure.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] For fire safety, the systems can be designed to have a greater ability to handle higher temperatures and continue to operate.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In dealing with security, the embedded systems can be self-sufficient and be able to deal with cut electrical and communication systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Miniature wireless devices called motes are networked wireless sensors.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] These motes are completely self-contained and will typically run off a battery source for years before the batteries need to be changed or charged.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Embedded systems are designed to perform a specific task, in contrast with general-purpose computers designed for multiple tasks.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Some have real-time performance constraints that must be met, for reasons such as safety and usability; others may have low or no performance requirements, allowing the system hardware to be simplified to reduce costs.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Embedded systems are not always standalone devices.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Many embedded systems are a small part within a larger device that serves a more general purpose.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] For example, the Gibson Robot Guitar features an embedded system for tuning the strings, but the overall purpose of the Robot Guitar is to play music.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Similarly, an embedded system in an automobile provides a specific function as a subsystem of the car itself.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The program instructions written for embedded systems are referred to as firmware, and are stored in read-only memory or flash memory chips.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] They run with limited computer hardware resources: little memory, small or non-existent keyboard or screen.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Embedded systems range from no user interface at all, in systems dedicated to one task, to complex graphical user interfaces that resemble modern computer desktop operating systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Simple embedded devices use buttons, light-emitting diodes (LED), graphic or character liquid-crystal displays (LCD) with a simple menu system.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] More sophisticated devices that use a graphical screen with touch sensing or screen-edge soft keys provide flexibility while minimizing space used: the meaning of the buttons can change with the screen, and selection involves the natural behavior of pointing at what is desired.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Some systems provide user interface remotely with the help of a serial (e.g.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] This approach extends the capabilities of the embedded system, avoids the cost of a display, simplifies the board support package (BSP) and allows designers to build a rich user interface on the PC.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] A good example of this is the combination of an embedded HTTP server running on an embedded device (such as an IP camera or a network router).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The user interface is displayed in a web browser on a PC connected to the device.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Examples of properties of typical embedded computers when compared with general-purpose counterparts are low power consumption, small size, rugged operating ranges, and low per-unit cost.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] This comes at the expense of limited processing resources.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Numerous microcontrollers have been developed for embedded systems use.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] General-purpose microprocessors are also used in embedded systems, but generally require more support circuitry than microcontrollers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] PC/104 and PC/104+ are examples of standards for ready-made computer boards intended for small, low-volume embedded and ruggedized systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] These are mostly x86-based and often physically small compared to a standard PC, although still large compared to most simple (8/16-bit) embedded systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] They may use a standard operating system such as Linux or NetBSD or an embedded real-time operating system (RTOS) such as MicroC/OS-II, QNX or VxWorks.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In certain applications, where small size or power efficiency are not primary concerns, the components used may be compatible with those used in general-purpose x86 personal computers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Boards such as the VIA EPIA range help to bridge the gap by being PC-compatible but highly integrated, physically smaller or have other attributes making them attractive to embedded engineers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The advantage of this approach is that low-cost commodity components may be used along with the same software development tools used for general software development.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Systems built in this way are still regarded as embedded since they are integrated into larger devices and fulfill a single role.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Examples of devices that may adopt this approach are automated teller machines (ATM) and arcade machines, which contain code specific to the application.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] However, most ready-made embedded systems boards are not PC-centered and do not use the ISA or PCI buses.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] When a system-on-a-chip processor is involved, there may be little benefit to having a standardized bus connecting discrete components, and the environment for both hardware and software tools may be very different.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] One common design style uses a small system module, perhaps the size of a business card, holding high density BGA chips such as an ARM-based system-on-a-chip processor and peripherals, external flash memory for storage, and DRAM for runtime memory.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The module vendor will usually provide boot software and make sure there is a selection of operating systems, usually including Linux and some real-time choices.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] These modules can be manufactured in high volume, by organizations familiar with their specialized testing issues and combined with much lower volume custom mainboards with application-specific external peripherals.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Prominent examples of this approach include Arduino and Raspberry Pi.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] A system on a chip (SoC) contains a complete system - consisting of multiple processors, multipliers, caches, even different types of memory and commonly various peripherals like interfaces for wired or wireless communication on a single chip.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Often graphics processing units (GPU) and DSPs are included such chips.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] SoCs can be implemented as an application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) or using a field-programmable gate array (FPGA), which typically can be reconfigured.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] ASIC implementations are common for very-high-volume embedded systems like mobile phones and smartphones.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] ASIC or FPGA implementations may be used for not-so-high-volume embedded systems with special needs in terms of signal processing performance, interfaces and reliability, like in avionics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] As with other software, embedded system designers use compilers, assemblers, and debuggers to develop embedded system software.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Embedded software often requires a variety of development tools, including programming languages such as C++, Rust, or Python, and frameworks like Qt for graphical interfaces.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] These tools enable developers to create efficient, scalable, and feature-rich applications tailored to the specific requirements of embedded systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The choice of tools is driven by factors such as real-time performance, integration with hardware, or energy efficiency.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] As the complexity of embedded systems grows, higher-level tools and operating systems are migrating into machinery where it makes sense.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] For example, cellphones, personal digital assistants and other consumer computers often need significant software that is purchased or provided by a person other than the manufacturer of the electronics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In these systems, an open programming environment such as Linux, NetBSD, FreeBSD, OSGi or Embedded Java is required so that the third-party software provider can sell to a large market.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Embedded debugging may be performed at different levels, depending on the facilities available.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Unless restricted to external debugging, the programmer can typically load and run software through the tools, view the code running in the processor, and start or stop its operation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The view of the code may be as high-level programming language, assembly code or a mixture of both.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Real-time operating systems often support tracing of operating system events.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] A graphical view is presented by a host PC tool, based on a recording of the system behavior.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The trace recording can be performed in software, by the RTOS, or by special tracing hardware.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] RTOS tracing allows developers to understand timing and performance issues of the software system and gives a good understanding of the high-level system behaviors.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Trace recording in embedded systems can be achieved using hardware or software solutions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Software-based trace recording does not require specialized debugging hardware and can be used to record traces in deployed devices, but it can have an impact on CPU and RAM usage.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] One example of a software-based tracing method used in RTOS environments is the use of empty macros which are invoked by the operating system at strategic places in the code, and can be implemented to serve as hooks.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Embedded systems often reside in machines that are expected to run continuously for years without error, and in some cases, recover by themselves if an error occurs.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Therefore, the software is usually developed and tested more carefully than that for personal computers, and unreliable mechanical moving parts such as disk drives, switches or buttons are avoided.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] For high-volume systems such as mobile phones, minimizing cost is usually the primary design consideration.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Engineers typically select hardware that is just good enough to implement the necessary functions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] For low-volume or prototype embedded systems, general-purpose computers may be adapted by limiting the programs or by replacing the operating system with an RTOS.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In 1978 National Electrical Manufacturers Association released ICS 3-1978, a standard for programmable microcontrollers, including almost any computer-based controllers, such as single-board computers, numerical, and event-based controllers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] There are several different types of software architecture in common use.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In this design, the software simply has a loop which monitors the input devices.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The loop calls subroutines, each of which manages a part of the hardware or software.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Hence it is called a simple control loop or programmed input-output.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Some embedded systems are predominantly controlled by interrupts.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] This means that tasks performed by the system are triggered by different kinds of events; an interrupt could be generated, for example, by a timer at a predefined interval, or by a serial port controller receiving data.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] This architecture is used if event handlers need low latency, and the event handlers are short and simple.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] These systems run a simple task in a main loop also, but this task is not very sensitive to unexpected delays.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Sometimes the interrupt handler will add longer tasks to a queue structure.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Later, after the interrupt handler has finished, these tasks are executed by the main loop.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] This method brings the system close to a multitasking kernel with discrete processes.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Cooperative multitasking is very similar to the simple control loop scheme, except that the loop is hidden in an API.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The programmer defines a series of tasks, and each task gets its own environment to run in.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] When a task is idle, it calls an idle routine, which passes control to another task.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The advantages and disadvantages are similar to those of the control loop, except that adding new software is easier, by simply writing a new task, or adding to the queue.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In this type of system, a low-level piece of code switches between tasks or threads based on a timer that invokes an interrupt.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] This is the level at which the system is generally considered to have an operating system kernel.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Depending on how much functionality is required, it introduces more or less of the complexities associated with managing multiple tasks running conceptually in parallel.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Because of these complexities, it is common for organizations to use an off-the-shelf RTOS, allowing the application programmers to concentrate on device functionality rather than operating system services.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The choice to include an RTOS brings in its own issues, however, as the selection must be made prior to starting the application development process.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] This timing forces developers to choose the embedded operating system for their device based on current requirements and so restricts future options to a large extent.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] These trends are leading to the uptake of embedded middleware in addition to an RTOS.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] A microkernel allocates memory and switches the CPU to different threads of execution.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] User-mode processes implement major functions such as file systems, network interfaces, etc.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Exokernels communicate efficiently by normal subroutine calls.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] The hardware and all the software in the system are available to and extensible by application programmers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] A monolithic kernel is a relatively large kernel with sophisticated capabilities adapted to suit an embedded environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] This gives programmers an environment similar to a desktop operating system like Linux or Microsoft Windows, and is therefore very productive for development.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] On the downside, it requires considerably more hardware resources, is often more expensive, and, because of the complexity of these kernels, can be less predictable and reliable.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Common examples of embedded monolithic kernels are embedded Linux, VXWorks and Windows CE.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] Despite the increased cost in hardware, this type of embedded system is increasing in popularity, especially on the more powerful embedded devices such as wireless routers and GPS navigation systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In addition to the core operating system, many embedded systems have additional upper-layer software components.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] These components include networking protocol stacks like CAN, TCP/IP, FTP, HTTP, and HTTPS, and storage capabilities like FAT and flash memory management systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] If the embedded device has audio and video capabilities, then the appropriate drivers and codecs will be present in the system.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In the case of the monolithic kernels, many of these software layers may be included in the kernel.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In the RTOS category, the availability of additional software components depends on the commercial offering.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/embedded-system] In the automotive sector, AUTOSAR is a standard architecture for embedded software.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] HIL simulation must include electrical emulation of sensors and actuators.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] These electrical emulations act as the interface between the plant simulation and the embedded system under test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The value of each electrically emulated sensor is controlled by the plant simulation and is read by the embedded system under test (feedback).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Likewise, the embedded system under test implements its control algorithms by outputting actuator control signals.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Changes in the control signals result in changes to variable values in the plant simulation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In many cases, the most effective way to develop an embedded system is to connect the embedded system to the real plant.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In other cases, HIL simulation is more efficient.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The metric of development and testing efficiency is typically a formula that includes the following factors: 1.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The cost of the approach should be a measure of the cost of all tools and effort.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The duration of development and testing affects the time-to-market for a planned product.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Safety factor and development duration are typically equated to a cost measure.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Usage of HILs enhances the quality of the testing by increasing the scope of the testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Ideally, an embedded system would be tested against the real plant, but most of the time the real plant itself imposes limitations in terms of the scope of the testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In the above-mentioned test scenarios, HIL provides the efficient control and safe environment where test or application engineer can focus on the functionality of the controller.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The tight development schedules associated with most new automotive, aerospace and defense programs do not allow embedded system testing to wait for a prototype to be available.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In fact, most new development schedules assume that HIL simulation will be used in parallel with the development of the plant.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] For example, by the time a new automobile engine prototype is made available for control system testing, 95% of the engine controller testing will have been completed using HIL simulation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The aerospace and defense industries are even more likely to impose a tight development schedule.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Aircraft and land vehicle development programs are using desktop and HIL simulation to perform design, test, and integration in parallel.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In many cases, the plant is more expensive than a high fidelity, real-time simulator and therefore has a higher-burden rate.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Therefore, it is more economical to develop and test while connected to a HIL simulator than the real plant.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] For jet engine manufacturers, HIL simulation is a fundamental part of engine development.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The development of Full Authority Digital Engine Controllers (FADEC) for aircraft jet engines is an extreme example of a high-burden-rate plant.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Each jet engine can cost millions of dollars.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In contrast, a HIL simulator designed to test a jet engine manufacturer's complete line of engines may demand merely a tenth of the cost of a single engine.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] HIL simulation is a key step in the process of developing human factors, a method of ensuring usability and system consistency using software ergonomics, human-factors research and design.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] For real-time technology, human-factors development is the task of collecting usability data from man-in-the-loop testing for components that will have a human interface.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] An example of usability testing is the development of fly-by-wire flight controls.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Fly-by-wire flight controls eliminate the mechanical linkages between the flight controls and the aircraft control surfaces.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Sensors communicate the demanded flight response and then apply realistic force feedback to the fly-by-wire controls using motors.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The behavior of fly-by-wire flight controls is defined by control algorithms.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Changes in algorithm parameters can translate into more or less flight response from a given flight control input.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Likewise, changes in the algorithm parameters can also translate into more or less force feedback for a given flight control input.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The “correct” parameter values are a subjective measure.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Therefore, it is important to get input from numerous man-in-the-loop tests to obtain optimal parameter values.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In the case of fly-by-wire flight controls development, HIL simulation is used to simulate human factors.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The flight simulator includes plant simulations of aerodynamics, engine thrust, environmental conditions, flight control dynamics and more.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Prototype fly-by-wire flight controls are connected to the simulator and test pilots evaluate flight performance given various algorithm parameters.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The alternative to HIL simulation for human factors and usability development is to place prototype flight controls in early aircraft prototypes and test for usability during flight test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] This approach fails when measuring the four conditions listed above.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] *Cost:* A flight test is extremely costly and therefore the goal is to minimize any development occurring with flight test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] *Duration:* Developing flight controls with flight test will extend the duration of an aircraft development program.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Using HIL simulation, the flight controls may be developed well before a real aircraft is available.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] *Safety:* Using flight test for the development of critical components such as flight controls has a major safety implication.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Should errors be present in the design of the prototype flight controls, the result could be a crash landing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] *Feasibility:* It may not be possible to explore certain critical timings (e.g. sequences of user actions with millisecond precision) with real users operating a plant.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Likewise for problematical points in parameter space that may not be easily reachable with a real plant but must be tested against the hardware in question.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In a typical HIL Simulator, a dedicated real-time processor executes mathematical models which emulate engine dynamics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In addition, an I/O unit allows the connection of vehicle sensors and actuators (which usually present high degree of non-linearity).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Finally, the Electronic Control Unit (ECU) under test is connected to the system and stimulated by a set of vehicle maneuvers executed by the simulator.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] At this point, HIL simulation also offers a high degree of repeatability during testing phase.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In the literature, several HIL specific applications are reported and simplified HIL simulators were built according to some specific purpose.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] When testing a new ECU software release for example, experiments can be performed in open loop and therefore several engine dynamic models are no longer required.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The strategy is restricted to the analysis of ECU outputs when excited by controlled inputs.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In this case, a Micro HIL system (MHIL) offers a simpler and more economic solution.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Since complexity of models processing is dumped, a full-size HIL system is reduced into a portable device composed of a signal generator, an I/O board, and a console containing the actuators (external loads) to be connected to the ECU.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] HIL simulation for radar systems have evolved from radar-jamming.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Digital Radio Frequency Memory (DRFM) systems are typically used to create false targets to confuse the radar in the battlefield, but these same systems can simulate a target in the laboratory.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] This configuration allows for the testing and evaluation of the radar system, reducing the need for flight trials (for airborne radar systems) and field tests (for search or tracking radars), and can give an early indication to the susceptibility of the radar to electronic warfare (EW) techniques.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Techniques for HIL simulation have been recently applied to the automatic generation of complex controllers for robots.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] A robot uses its own real hardware to extract sensation and actuation data, then uses this data to infer a physical simulation (self-model) containing aspects such as its own morphology as well as characteristics of the environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Algorithms such as Back-to-Reality (BTR) and Estimation Exploration (EEA) have been proposed in this context.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In recent years, HIL for power systems has been used for verifying the stability, operation, and fault tolerance of large-scale electrical grids.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Current-generation real-time processing platforms have the capability to model large-scale power systems in real-time.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] This includes systems with more than 10,000 buses with associated generators, loads, power-factor correction devices, and network interconnections.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] These types of simulation platforms enable the evaluation and testing of large-scale power systems in a realistic emulated environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Moreover, HIL for power systems has been used for investigating the integration of distributed resources, next-generation SCADA systems and power management units, and static synchronous compensator devices.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] In offshore and marine engineering, control systems and mechanical structures are generally designed in parallel.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Testing the control systems is only possible after integration.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] As a result, many errors are found that have to be solved during the commissioning, with the risks of personal injuries, damaging equipment and delays.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] To reduce these errors, HIL simulation is gaining widespread attention.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] This is reflected by the adoption of HIL simulation in the Det Norske Veritas rules.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Simulating sensor feedback to missile guidance systems allows developers to simulate the attitude sensors and record the drive to thrust vectoring systems and aerodynamic control surface devices to test their control algorithms in the lab.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] Providing fault conditions to missile control system sensors allows observation of the how guidance systems respond to those faults.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/hardware-in-the-loop-simulation] The resilience of the system can be observed and subsequently improved using this technique.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is also used in simulation to mean that the simulation's clock runs at the same speed as a real clock.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Real-time responses are often understood to be in the order of milliseconds, and sometimes microseconds.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] A system not specified as operating in real time cannot usually *guarantee* a response within any timeframe, although *typical* or *expected* response times may be given.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Real-time processing *fails* if not completed within a specified deadline relative to an event; deadlines must always be met, regardless of system load.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] A real-time system has been described as one which "controls an environment by receiving data, processing them, and returning the results sufficiently quickly to affect the environment at that time".
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] The term "real-time" is used in process control and enterprise systems to mean "without significant delay".
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Real-time software may use one or more of the following: synchronous programming languages, real-time operating systems (RTOSes), and real-time networks.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Each of these provides essential frameworks on which to build a real-time software application.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Systems used for many safety-critical applications must be real-time, such as for control of fly-by-wire aircraft, or anti-lock brakes, both of which demand immediate and accurate mechanical response.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] The term *real-time* derives from its use in early simulation, where a real-world process is simulated at a rate which matched that of the real process (now called real-time simulation to avoid ambiguity).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Analog computers, most often, were capable of simulating at a much faster pace than real-time, a situation that could be just as dangerous as a slow simulation if it were not also recognized and accounted for.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Minicomputers, particularly from the 1970s onwards, when built into dedicated embedded systems such as DOG (digital on-screen graphic) scanners, increased the need for low-latency priority-driven responses to important interactions with incoming data.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Operating systems such as Data General's RDOS (Real-Time Disk Operating System) and RTOS with background and foreground scheduling as well as Digital Equipment Corporation's RT-11 date from this era.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Background-foreground scheduling allowed low-priority tasks CPU time when no foreground task needed to execute, and gave absolute priority within the foreground to threads/tasks with the highest priority.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Real-time operating systems would also be used for time-sharing multiuser duties.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] For example, Data General Business Basic could run in the foreground or background of RDOS and would introduce additional elements to the scheduling algorithm to make it more appropriate for people interacting via dumb terminals.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Early personal computers were sometimes used for real-time computing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] The possibility of deactivating other interrupts allowed for hard-coded loops with defined timing, and the low interrupt latency allowed the implementation of a real-time operating system, giving the user interface and the disk drives lower priority than the real-time thread.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] However, several coding libraries exist that offer real-time capabilities in a high-level language on a variety of operating systems, for example, Real-time Java.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Later microprocessors such as the Motorola 68000 and subsequent family members (68010, 68020, ColdFire, etc.) also became popular with manufacturers of industrial control systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] This application area is one where real-time control offers genuine advantages in terms of process performance and safety.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] A system is said to be *real-time* if the total correctness of an operation depends not only upon its logical correctness, but also upon the time in which it is performed.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Thus, the goal of a *hard real-time system* is to ensure that all deadlines are met, but for *soft real-time systems* the goal becomes meeting a certain subset of deadlines in order to optimize some application-specific criteria.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] The particular criteria optimized depend on the application, but some typical examples include maximizing the number of deadlines met, minimizing the lateness of tasks and maximizing the number of high-priority tasks meeting their deadlines.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] In the context of multitasking systems the scheduling policy is normally priority driven (pre-emptive schedulers).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] In some situations, these can guarantee hard real-time performance (for instance, if the set of tasks and their priorities is known in advance).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] There are other hard real-time schedulers such as rate-monotonic, which is not common in general-purpose systems, as it requires additional information in order to schedule a task: namely, a bound or worst-case estimate for how long the task must execute.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Specific algorithms for scheduling such hard real-time tasks exist, like earliest deadline first, which, ignoring the overhead of context switching, is sufficient for system loads of less than 100%.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] New overlay scheduling systems, such as an adaptive partition scheduler assist in managing large systems with a mixture of hard real-time and non real-time applications.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] In a real-time digital signal processing (DSP) process, the analyzed (input) and generated (output) samples can be processed (or generated) continuously in the time it takes to input and output the same set of samples *independent* of the processing delay.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] It means that the processing delay must be bounded even if the processing continues for an unlimited time.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] The mean processing time per sample, including overhead, is no greater than the sampling period, which is the reciprocal of the sampling rate.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] This is the criterion whether the samples are grouped together in large segments and processed as blocks or are processed individually and whether there are long, short, or non-existent input and output buffers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Consider an audio DSP example; if a process requires 2.01 seconds to analyze, synthesize, or process 2.00 seconds of sound, it is not real-time.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] However, if it takes 1.99 seconds, it is or can be made into a real-time DSP process.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] A common life analogy is standing in a line or queue waiting for the checkout in a grocery store.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] If the line asymptotically grows longer and longer without bound, the checkout process is not real-time.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] If the length of the line is bounded, customers are being "processed" and output as rapidly, on average, as they are being inputted, then that process *is* real-time.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] The grocer might go out of business or must at least lose business if they cannot make their checkout process real-time; thus, it is fundamentally important that this process is real-time.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] A signal processing algorithm that cannot keep up with the flow of input data, with output falling further and further behind the input, is not real-time.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] If the delay of the output (relative to the input) is bounded regarding a process that operates over an unlimited time, then that signal processing algorithm is real-time, even if the throughput delay may be very long.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Real-time signal processing is necessary, but not sufficient in and of itself, for live signal processing such as what is required in live event support.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Live audio digital signal processing requires both real-time operation and a sufficient limit to throughput delay so as to be tolerable to performers using stage monitors or in-ear monitors and not noticeable as lip sync error by the audience also directly watching the performers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Tolerable limits to latency for live, real-time processing is a subject of investigation and debate, but is estimated to be between 6 and 20 milliseconds.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Real-time bidirectional telecommunications delays of less than 300 ms ("round trip" or twice the unidirectional delay) are considered "acceptable" to avoid undesired "talk-over" in conversation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Real-time computing is sometimes misunderstood to be high-performance computing, but this is not an accurate classification.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] For example, a massive supercomputer executing a scientific simulation may offer impressive performance, yet it is not executing a real-time computation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Conversely, once the hardware and software for an anti-lock braking system have been designed to meet its required deadlines, no further performance gains are obligatory or even useful.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Furthermore, if a network server is highly loaded with network traffic, its response time may be slower, but will (in most cases) still succeed before it times out (hits its deadline).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Hence, such a network server would not be considered a real-time system: temporal failures (delays, time-outs, etc.) are typically small and compartmentalized (limited in effect), but are not catastrophic failures.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] In a real-time system, such as the FTSE 100 Index, a slowdown beyond limits would often be considered catastrophic in its application context.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] The most important requirement of a real-time system is consistent output, not high throughput.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Some kinds of software, such as many chess-playing programs, can fall into either category.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] For instance, a chess program designed to play in a tournament with a clock will need to decide on a move before a certain deadline or lose the game, and is therefore a real-time computation, but a chess program that is allowed to run indefinitely before moving is not.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] In both of these cases, however, high performance is desirable: the more work a tournament chess program can do in the allotted time, the better its moves will be, and the faster an unconstrained chess program runs, the sooner it will be able to move.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] High performance is indicative of the amount of processing that is performed in a given amount of time, whereas real-time is the ability to get done with the processing to yield a useful output in the available time.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] For example, a near-real-time display depicts an event or situation as it existed at the current time minus the processing time, as nearly the time of the live event.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] The distinction between the terms "near real time" and "real time" is somewhat nebulous and must be defined for the situation at hand.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] The term implies that there are no significant delays.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] In many cases, processing described as "real-time" would be more accurately described as "near real-time".
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Near real-time also refers to delayed real-time transmission of voice and video.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] It allows playing video images, in approximately real-time, without having to wait for an entire large video file to download.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Incompatible databases can export/import to common flat files that the other database can import/export on a scheduled basis so they can sync/share common data in "near real-time" with each other.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Several methods exist to aid the design of real-time systems, an example of which is MASCOT, an old but very successful method that represents the concurrent structure of the system.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/real-time-computing] Other examples are HOOD, Real-Time UML, AADL, the Ravenscar profile, and Real-time Java.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] A **simulation** is an imitative representation of a process or system that could exist in the real world.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] In this broad sense, simulation can often be used interchangeably with model.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Sometimes a clear distinction between the two terms is made, in which simulations require the use of models; the model represents the key characteristics or behaviors of the selected system or process, whereas the simulation represents the evolution of the model over time.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Another way to distinguish between the terms is to define simulation as experimentation with the help of a model.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] This definition includes time-independent simulations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Often, computers are used to execute the simulation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulation is used in many contexts, such as simulation of technology for performance tuning or optimizing, safety engineering, testing, training, education, and video games.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulation is also used with scientific modelling of natural systems or human systems to gain insight into their functioning, as in economics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulation can be used to show the eventual real effects of alternative conditions and courses of action.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulation is also used when the real system cannot be engaged, because it may not be accessible, or it may be dangerous or unacceptable to engage, or it is being designed but not yet built, or it may simply not exist.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Procedures and protocols for model verification and validation are an ongoing field of academic study, refinement, research and development in simulations technology or practice, particularly in the work of computer simulation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Historically, simulations used in different fields developed largely independently, but 20th-century studies of systems theory and cybernetics combined with the spreading use of computers across all those fields have led to some unification and a more systematic view of the concept.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] A *stand-alone simulation* is a simulation running on a single workstation by itself.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] A **distributed simulation** is one which uses more than one computer simultaneously, to guarantee access from/to different resources (e.g. multi-users operating different systems, or distributed data sets); a classical example is Distributed Interactive Simulation (DIS).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] A *synthetic environment* is a computer simulation that can be included in human-in-the-loop simulations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Data simulation creates artificial data to replicate the behavior of real-world data.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The artificial data is generated using computer models or programs based on specific rules, patterns, or characteristics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] This type of data is designed to imitate the operations of real systems, processes, or behaviors, enabling researchers and analysts to study and test scenarios without directly observing or collecting information from the real world.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] A computer simulation (or "sim") is an attempt to model a real-life or hypothetical situation on a computer so that it can be studied to see how the system works.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] By changing variables in the simulation, predictions may be made about the behaviour of the system.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] It is a tool to virtually investigate the behaviour of the system under study.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Computer simulation has become a useful part of modeling many natural systems in physics, chemistry and biology, and human systems in economics and social science (e.g., computational sociology) as well as in engineering to gain insight into the operation of those systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] A good example of the usefulness of using computers to simulate can be found in the field of network traffic simulation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] In such simulations, the model behaviour will change each simulation according to the set of initial parameters assumed for the environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Traditionally, the formal modeling of systems has been via a mathematical model, which attempts to find analytical solutions enabling the prediction of the behaviour of the system from a set of parameters and initial conditions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Computer simulation is often used as an adjunct to, or substitution for, modeling systems for which simple closed form analytic solutions are not possible.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] There are many different types of computer simulation, the common feature they all share is the attempt to generate a sample of representative scenarios for a model in which a complete enumeration of all possible states would be prohibitive or impossible.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Several software packages exist for running computer-based simulation modeling (e.g.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Monte Carlo simulation, stochastic modeling, multimethod modeling) that makes all the modeling almost effortless.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Modern usage of the term "computer simulation" may encompass virtually any computer-based representation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The computer simulates the subject machine.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Accordingly, in theoretical computer science the term *simulation* is a relation between state transition systems, useful in the study of operational semantics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Less theoretically, an interesting application of computer simulation is to simulate computers using computers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] For example, simulators have been used to debug a microprogram or sometimes commercial application programs, before the program is downloaded to the target machine.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Since the operation of the computer is simulated, all of the information about the computer's operation is directly available to the programmer, and the speed and execution of the simulation can be varied at will.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulators may also be used to interpret fault trees, or test VLSI logic designs before they are constructed.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Symbolic simulation uses variables to stand for unknown values.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] In the field of optimization, simulations of physical processes are often used in conjunction with evolutionary computation to optimize control strategies.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulation is extensively used for educational purposes.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] It is used for cases where it is prohibitively expensive or simply too dangerous to allow trainees to use the real equipment in the real world.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] In such situations they will spend time learning valuable lessons in a "safe" virtual environment yet living a lifelike experience (or at least it is the goal).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Often the convenience is to permit mistakes during training for a safety-critical system.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulations in education are somewhat like training simulations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The term 'microworld' is used to refer to educational simulations which model some abstract concept rather than simulating a realistic object or environment, or in some cases model a real-world environment in a simplistic way so as to help a learner develop an understanding of the key concepts.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Normally, a user can create some sort of construction within the microworld that will behave in a way consistent with the concepts being modeled.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Seymour Papert was one of the first to advocate the value of microworlds, and the Logo programming environment developed by Papert is one of the most well-known microworlds.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Project management simulation is increasingly used to train students and professionals in the art and science of project management.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Using simulation for project management training improves learning retention and enhances the learning process.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] In recent years, there has been increasing use of social simulations for staff training in aid and development agencies.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The Carana simulation, for example, was first developed by the United Nations Development Programme, and is now used in a very revised form by the World Bank for training staff to deal with fragile and conflict-affected countries.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Military uses for simulation often involve aircraft or armoured fighting vehicles, but can also target small arms and other weapon systems training.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Specifically, virtual firearms ranges have become the norm in most military training processes and there is a significant amount of data to suggest this is a useful tool for armed professionals.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] A **virtual simulation** is a category of simulation that uses simulation equipment to create a **simulated world** for the user.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Virtual simulations allow users to interact with a virtual world.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Virtual worlds operate on platforms of integrated software and hardware components.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] In this manner, the system can accept input from the user (e.g., body tracking, voice/sound recognition, physical controllers) and produce output to the user (e.g., visual display, aural display, haptic display) .
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Virtual simulations use the aforementioned modes of interaction to produce a sense of immersion for the user.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] There is a wide variety of input hardware available to accept user input for virtual simulations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Research in future input systems holds a great deal of promise for virtual simulations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Systems such as brain–computer interfaces (BCIs) offer the ability to further increase the level of immersion for virtual simulation users.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Lee, Keinrath, Scherer, Bischof, Pfurtscheller proved that naïve subjects could be trained to use a BCI to navigate a virtual apartment with relative ease.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Using the BCI, the authors found that subjects were able to freely navigate the virtual environment with relatively minimal effort.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] It is possible that these types of systems will become standard input modalities in future virtual simulation systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] There is a wide variety of output hardware available to deliver stimuli to users in virtual simulations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Many medical simulators involve a computer connected to a plastic simulation of the relevant anatomy.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Sophisticated simulators of this type employ a life-size mannequin that responds to injected drugs and can be programmed to create simulations of life-threatening emergencies.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] In other simulations, visual components of the procedure are reproduced by computer graphics techniques, while touch-based components are reproduced by haptic feedback devices combined with physical simulation routines computed in response to the user's actions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Medical simulations of this sort will often use 3D CT or MRI scans of patient data to enhance realism.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Some medical simulations are developed to be widely distributed (such as web-enabled simulations and procedural simulations that can be viewed via standard web browsers) and can be interacted with using standard computer interfaces, such as the keyboard and mouse.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] An important medical application of a simulator—although, perhaps, denoting a slightly different meaning of *simulator*—is the use of a placebo drug, a formulation that simulates the active drug in trials of drug efficacy.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Patient safety is a concern in the medical industry.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Patients have been known to suffer injuries and even death due to management error, and lack of using best standards of care and training.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulation is being used to study patient safety, as well as train medical professionals.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Studying patient safety and safety interventions in healthcare is challenging, because there is a lack of experimental control (i.e., patient complexity, system/process variances) to see if an intervention made a meaningful difference (Groves & Manges, 2017).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] An example of innovative simulation to study patient safety is from nursing research.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] (2016) used a high-fidelity simulation to examine nursing safety-oriented behaviors during times such as change-of-shift report.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] However, the value of simulation interventions to translating to clinical practice are is still debatable.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] As Nishisaki states, "there is good evidence that simulation training improves provider and team self-efficacy and competence on manikins.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] There is also good evidence that procedural simulation improves actual operational performance in clinical settings." However, there is a need to have improved evidence to show that crew resource management training through simulation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] One of the largest challenges is showing that team simulation improves team operational performance at the bedside.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Although evidence that simulation-based training actually improves patient outcome has been slow to accrue, today the ability of simulation to provide hands-on experience that translates to the operating room is no longer in doubt.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] One of the largest factors that might impact the ability to have training impact the work of practitioners at the bedside is the ability to empower frontline staff (Stewart, Manges, Ward, 2015).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Another example of an attempt to improve patient safety through the use of simulations training is patient care to deliver just-in-time service or/and just-in-place.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] This training consists of 20 minutes of simulated training just before workers report to shift.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] One study found that just in time training improved the transition to the bedside.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The conclusion as reported in Nishisaki (2008) work, was that the simulation training improved resident participation in real cases; but did not sacrifice the quality of service.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] It could be therefore hypothesized that by increasing the number of highly trained residents through the use of simulation training, that the simulation training does, in fact, increase patient safety.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The first medical simulators were simple models of human patients.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Since antiquity, these representations in clay and stone were used to demonstrate clinical features of disease states and their effects on humans.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Models have been found in many cultures and continents.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] These models have been used in some cultures (e.g., Chinese culture) as a "diagnostic" instrument, allowing women to consult male physicians while maintaining social laws of modesty.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Models are used today to help students learn the anatomy of the musculoskeletal system and organ systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The need for a "uniform mechanism to educate, evaluate, and certify simulation instructors for the health care profession" was recognized by McGaghie et al. in their critical review of simulation-based medical education research.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] In 2012 the SSH piloted two new certifications to provide recognition to educators in an effort to meet this need.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Active models that attempt to reproduce living anatomy or physiology are recent developments.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The famous "Harvey" mannequin was developed at the University of Miami and is able to recreate many of the physical findings of the cardiology examination, including palpation, auscultation, and electrocardiography.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] More recently, interactive models have been developed that respond to actions taken by a student or physician.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Until recently, these simulations were two dimensional computer programs that acted more like a textbook than a patient.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Computer simulations have the advantage of allowing a student to make judgments, and also to make errors.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The process of iterative learning through assessment, evaluation, decision making, and error correction creates a much stronger learning environment than passive instruction.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulators have been proposed as an ideal tool for assessment of students for clinical skills.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] For patients, "cybertherapy" can be used for sessions simulating traumatic experiences, from fear of heights to social anxiety.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Programmed patients and simulated clinical situations, including mock disaster drills, have been used extensively for education and evaluation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] These "lifelike" simulations are expensive, and lack reproducibility.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] A fully functional "3Di" simulator would be the most specific tool available for teaching and measurement of clinical skills.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Gaming platforms have been applied to create these virtual medical environments to create an interactive method for learning and application of information in a clinical context.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Immersive disease state simulations allow a doctor or HCP to experience what a disease actually feels like.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Using sensors and transducers, symptomatic effects can be delivered to a participant, allowing them to experience the patient’s disease state.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Such a simulator meets the goals of an objective and standardized examination for clinical competence.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] This system is superior to examinations that use "standard patients" because it permits the quantitative measurement of competence, as well as reproducing the same objective findings.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The first simulation game may have been created as early as 1947 by Thomas T.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] This was a straightforward game that simulated a missile being fired at a target.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The curve of the missile and its speed could be adjusted using several knobs.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] In 1958, a computer game called *Tennis for Two* was created by Willy Higginbotham which simulated a tennis game between two players who could both play at the same time using hand controls and was displayed on an oscilloscope.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] This was one of the first electronic video games to use a graphical display.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Computer-generated imagery was used in the film to simulate objects as early as 1972 in *A Computer Animated Hand*, parts of which were shown on the big screen in the 1976 film *Futureworld*.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] This was followed by the "targeting computer" that young Skywalker turns off in the 1977 film *Star Wars*.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The film *Tron* (1982) was the first film to use computer-generated imagery for more than a couple of minutes.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Advances in technology in the 1980s caused 3D simulation to become more widely used and it began to appear in movies and in computer-based games such as Atari's *Battlezone* (1980) and Acornsoft's *Elite* (1984), one of the first wire-frame 3D graphics games for home computers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Advances in technology in the 1980s made the computer more affordable and more capable than they were in previous decades, which facilitated the rise of computer such as the Xbox gaming.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The first video game consoles released in the 1970s and early 1980s fell prey to the industry crash in 1983, but in 1985, Nintendo released the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES) which became one of the best selling consoles in video game history.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] In the 1990s, computer games became widely popular with the release of such game as *The Sims* and *Command & Conquer* and the still increasing power of desktop computers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Today, computer simulation games such as *World of Warcraft* are played by millions of people around the world.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] In 1993, the film *Jurassic Park* became the first popular film to use computer-generated graphics extensively, integrating the simulated dinosaurs almost seamlessly into live action scenes.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] This event transformed the film industry; in 1995, the film *Toy Story* was the first film to use only computer-generated images and by the new millennium computer generated graphics were the leading choice for special effects in films.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The advent of virtual cinematography in the early 2000s has led to an explosion of movies that would have been impossible to shoot without it.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Classic examples are the digital look-alikes of Neo, Smith and other characters in the *Matrix* sequels and the extensive use of physically impossible camera runs in *The Lord of the Rings* trilogy.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Computer-generated imagery is "the application of the field of 3D computer graphics to special effects".
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] This technology is used for visual effects because they are high in quality, controllable, and can create effects that would not be feasible using any other technology either because of cost, resources or safety.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Computer-generated graphics can be seen in many live-action movies today, especially those of the action genre.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Further, computer-generated imagery has almost completely supplanted hand-drawn animation in children's movies which are increasingly computer-generated only.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Examples of movies that use computer-generated imagery include *Finding Nemo*, *300* and *Iron Man*.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulation games, as opposed to other genres of video and computer games, represent or simulate an environment accurately.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Moreover, they represent the interactions between the playable characters and the environment realistically.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] These kinds of games are usually more complex in terms of gameplay.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulation games have become incredibly popular among people of all ages.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Popular simulation games include *SimCity* and *Tiger Woods PGA Tour*.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] There are also flight simulator and driving simulator games.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulators have been used for entertainment since the Link Trainer in the 1930s.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The first modern simulator ride to open at a theme park was Disney's Star Tours in 1987 soon followed by Universal's The Funtastic World of Hanna-Barbera in 1990 which was the first ride to be done entirely with computer graphics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Simulator rides are the progeny of military training simulators and commercial simulators, but they are different in a fundamental way.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] While military training simulators react realistically to the input of the trainee in real time, ride simulators only feel like they move realistically and move according to prerecorded motion scripts.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] One of the first simulator rides, Star Tours, which cost $32 million, used a hydraulic motion based cabin.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] The movement was programmed by a joystick.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Today's simulator rides, such as The Amazing Adventures of Spider-Man include elements to increase the amount of immersion experienced by the riders such as: 3D imagery, physical effects (spraying water or producing scents), and movement through an environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p01] Another important goal of simulation in manufacturing systems is to quantify system performance.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] An automobile simulator provides an opportunity to reproduce the characteristics of real vehicles in a virtual environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] It replicates the external factors and conditions with which a vehicle interacts enabling a driver to feel as if they are sitting in the cab of their own vehicle.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Scenarios and events are replicated with sufficient reality to ensure that drivers become fully immersed in the experience rather than simply viewing it as an educational experience.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The simulator provides a constructive experience for the novice driver and enables more complex exercises to be undertaken by the more mature driver.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] For novice drivers, truck simulators provide an opportunity to begin their career by applying best practice.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] For mature drivers, simulation provides the ability to enhance good driving or to detect poor practice and to suggest the necessary steps for remedial action.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] For companies, it provides an opportunity to educate staff in the driving skills that achieve reduced maintenance costs, improved productivity and, most importantly, to ensure the safety of their actions in all possible situations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] A **biomechanics simulator** is a simulation platform for creating dynamic mechanical models built from combinations of rigid and deformable bodies, joints, constraints, and various force actuators.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] It is specialized for creating biomechanical models of human anatomical structures, with the intention to study their function and eventually assist in the design and planning of medical treatment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] A biomechanics simulator is used to analyze walking dynamics, study sports performance, simulate surgical procedures, analyze joint loads, design medical devices, and animate human and animal movement.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] A neuromechanical simulator combines biomechanical and biologically realistic neural network simulation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] It allows the user to test hypotheses about the neural basis of behavior in a physically accurate 3D virtual environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] A city simulator can be a city-building game but can also be a tool used by urban planners to understand how cities are likely to evolve in response to various policy decisions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] AnyLogic is an example of modern, large-scale urban simulators designed for use by urban planners.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] City simulators are generally agent-based simulations with explicit representations for land use and transportation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] UrbanSim and LEAM are examples of large-scale urban simulation models that are used by metropolitan planning agencies and military bases for land use and transportation planning.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Several Christmas-themed simulations exist, many of which are centered around Santa Claus.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] An example of these simulations are websites which claim to allow the user to track Santa Claus.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Another example of these simulations are websites that claim to allow the user to email or send messages to Santa Claus.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Websites such as emailSanta.com or Santa's former page on the now-defunct Windows Live Spaces by Microsoft use automated programs or scripts to generate personalized replies claimed to be from Santa himself based on user input.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Modern satellite communications systems (SATCOM) are often large and complex with many interacting parts and elements.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] In addition, the need for broadband connectivity on a moving vehicle has increased dramatically in the past few years for both commercial and military applications.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] To accurately predict and deliver high quality of service, SATCOM system designers have to factor in terrain as well as atmospheric and meteorological conditions in their planning.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] To deal with such complexity, system designers and operators increasingly turn towards computer models of their systems to simulate real-world operating conditions and gain insights into usability and requirements prior to final product sign-off.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Modeling improves the understanding of the system by enabling the SATCOM system designer or planner to simulate real-world performance by injecting the models with multiple hypothetical atmospheric and environmental conditions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulation is often used in the training of civilian and military personnel.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] This usually occurs when it is prohibitively expensive or simply too dangerous to allow trainees to use the real equipment in the real world.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] In such situations, they will spend time learning valuable lessons in a "safe" virtual environment yet living a lifelike experience (or at least it is the goal).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulation solutions are being increasingly integrated with computer-aided solutions and processes (computer-aided design or CAD, computer-aided manufacturing or CAM, computer-aided engineering or CAE, etc.).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The use of simulation throughout the product lifecycle, especially at the earlier concept and design stages, has the potential of providing substantial benefits.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] These benefits range from direct cost issues such as reduced prototyping and shorter time-to-market to better performing products and higher margins.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] However, for some companies, simulation has not provided the expected benefits.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The successful use of simulation, early in the lifecycle, has been largely driven by increased integration of simulation tools with the entire set of CAD, CAM and product-lifecycle management solutions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulation solutions can now function across the extended enterprise in a multi-CAD environment, and include solutions for managing simulation data and processes and ensuring that simulation results are made part of the product lifecycle history.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulation training has become a method for preparing people for disasters.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulations can replicate emergency situations and track how learners respond thanks to a lifelike experience.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Disaster preparedness simulations can involve training on how to handle terrorism attacks, natural disasters, pandemic outbreaks, or other life-threatening emergencies.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] One organization that has used simulation training for disaster preparedness is CADE (Center for Advancement of Distance Education).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] CADE has used a video game to prepare emergency workers for multiple types of attacks.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The Emergency Simulation Program (ESP) at the British Columbia Institute of Technology (BCIT), Vancouver, British Columbia, Canada is another example of an organization that uses simulation to train for emergency situations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] At the University of Québec in Chicoutimi, a research team at the outdoor research and expertise laboratory (Laboratoire d'Expertise et de Recherche en Plein Air – LERPA) specializes in using wilderness backcountry accident simulations to verify emergency response coordination.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Instructionally, the benefits of emergency training through simulations are that learner performance can be tracked through the system.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] This allows the developer to make adjustments as necessary or alert the educator on topics that may require additional attention.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Other advantages are that the learner can be guided or trained on how to respond appropriately before continuing to the next emergency segment—this is an aspect that may not be available in the live environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Some emergency training simulators also allow for immediate feedback, while other simulations may provide a summary and instruct the learner to engage in the learning topic again.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] In a live-emergency situation, emergency responders do not have time to waste.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulation-training in this environment provides an opportunity for learners to gather as much information as they can and practice their knowledge in a safe environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] They can make mistakes without risk of endangering lives and be given the opportunity to correct their errors to prepare for the real-life emergency.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulation is an important feature in engineering systems or any system that involves many processes.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] For example, in electrical engineering, delay lines may be used to simulate propagation delay and phase shift caused by an actual transmission line.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Similarly, dummy loads may be used to simulate impedance without simulating propagation and is used in situations where propagation is unwanted.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] A simulator may imitate only a few of the operations and functions of the unit it simulates.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Most engineering simulations entail mathematical modeling and computer-assisted investigation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] There are many cases, however, where mathematical modeling is not reliable.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulation of fluid dynamics problems often require both mathematical and physical simulations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] In these cases the physical models require dynamic similitude.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Physical and chemical simulations have also direct realistic uses, rather than research uses; in chemical engineering, for example, process simulations are used to give the process parameters immediately used for operating chemical plants, such as oil refineries.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulators are also used for plant operator training.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] It is called Operator Training Simulator (OTS) and has been widely adopted by many industries from chemical to oil&gas and to the power industry.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] This created a safe and realistic virtual environment to train board operators and engineers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Mimic is capable of providing high fidelity dynamic models of nearly all chemical plants for operator training and control system testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Software tools typically calculate biomechanical properties including individual muscle forces, joint forces and moments.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Most of these tools employ standard ergonomic evaluation methods such as the NIOSH lifting equation and Rapid Upper Limb Assessment (RULA).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Some simulations also analyze physiological measures including metabolism, energy expenditure, and fatigue limits Cycle time studies, design and process validation, user comfort, reachability, and line of sight are other human-factors that may be examined in ergonomic simulation packages.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Modeling and simulation of a task can be performed by manually manipulating the virtual human in the simulated environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Some ergonomics simulation software permits interactive, real-time simulation and evaluation through actual human input via motion capture technologies.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] However, motion capture for ergonomics requires expensive equipment and the creation of props to represent the environment or product.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Some applications of ergonomic simulation in include analysis of solid waste collection, disaster management tasks, interactive gaming, automotive assembly line, virtual prototyping of rehabilitation aids, and aerospace product design.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Ford engineers use ergonomics simulation software to perform virtual product design reviews.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Using engineering data, the simulations assist evaluation of assembly ergonomics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The company uses Siemen's Jack and Jill ergonomics simulation software in improving worker safety and efficiency, without the need to build expensive prototypes.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] In finance, computer simulations are often used for scenario planning.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Risk-adjusted net present value, for example, is computed from well-defined but not always known (or fixed) inputs.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] By imitating the performance of the project under evaluation, simulation can provide a distribution of NPV over a range of discount rates and other variables.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulations are also often used to test a financial theory or the ability of a financial model.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulations are frequently used in financial training to engage participants in experiencing various historical as well as fictional situations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] There are stock market simulations, portfolio simulations, risk management simulations or models and forex simulations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Such simulations are typically based on stochastic asset models.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Using these simulations in a training program allows for the application of theory into a something akin to real life.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] As with other industries, the use of simulations can be technology or case-study driven.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Flight simulation is mainly used to train pilots outside of the aircraft.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] In comparison to training in flight, simulation-based training allows for practicing maneuvers or situations that may be impractical (or even dangerous) to perform in the aircraft while keeping the pilot and instructor in a relatively low-risk environment on the ground.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] For example, electrical system failures, instrument failures, hydraulic system failures, and even flight control failures can be simulated without risk to the crew or equipment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Instructors can also provide students with a higher concentration of training tasks in a given period of time than is usually possible in the aircraft.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Flight simulation also provides an economic advantage over training in an actual aircraft.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Once fuel, maintenance, and insurance costs are taken into account, the operating costs of an FSTD are usually substantially lower than the operating costs of the simulated aircraft.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] For some large transport category airplanes, the operating costs may be several times lower for the FSTD than the actual aircraft.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Another advantage is reduced environmental impact, as simulators don't contribute directly to carbon or noise emissions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] There also exist "engineering flight simulators" which are a key element of the aircraft design process.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Many benefits that come from a lower number of test flights like cost and safety improvements are described above, but there are some unique advantages.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Having a simulator available allows for faster design iteration cycle or using more test equipment than could be fit into a real aircraft.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Bearing resemblance to flight simulators, a **marine simulator** is meant for training of ship personnel.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulators like these are mostly used within maritime colleges, training institutions, and navies.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] They often consist of a replication of a ships' bridge, with the operating console(s), and a number of screens on which the virtual surroundings are projected.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Military simulations, also known informally as war games, are models in which theories of warfare can be tested and refined without the need for actual hostilities.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] They exist in many different forms, with varying degrees of realism.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] In recent times, their scope has widened to include not only military but also political and social factors (for example, the Nationlab series of strategic exercises in Latin America).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] While many governments make use of simulation, both individually and collaboratively, little is known about the model's specifics outside professional circles.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Network and distributed systems have been extensively simulated in other to understand the impact of new protocols and algorithms before their deployment in the actual systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The simulation can focus on different levels (physical layer, network layer, application layer), and evaluate different metrics (network bandwidth, resource consumption, service time, dropped packets, system availability).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulation techniques have also been applied to payment and securities settlement systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Among the main users are central banks, which are generally responsible for the oversight of market infrastructure and are entitled to contribute to the smooth functioning of payment systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Central banks have been using payment system simulations to evaluate things such as the adequacy or sufficiency of liquidity available ( in the form of account balances and intraday credit limits) to participants (mainly banks) to allow efficient settlement of payments.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The need for liquidity is also dependent on the availability and the type of netting procedures in the systems, thus some of the studies have a focus on system comparisons.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Another application is to evaluate risks related to events such as communication network breakdowns or the inability of participants to send payments (e.g. in case of possible bank failure).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] This kind of analysis falls under the concepts of stress testing or scenario analysis.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] A common way to conduct these simulations is to replicate the settlement logics of the real payment or securities settlement systems under analysis and then use real observed payment data.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] In case of system comparison or system development, naturally, also the other settlement logics need to be implemented.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] To perform stress testing and scenario analysis, the observed data needs to be altered, e.g. some payments delayed or removed.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] To analyze the levels of liquidity, initial liquidity levels are varied.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] System comparisons (benchmarking) or evaluations of new netting algorithms or rules are performed by running simulations with a fixed set of data and varying only the system setups.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] An inference is usually done by comparing the benchmark simulation results to the results of altered simulation setups by comparing indicators such as unsettled transactions or settlement delays.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Project management simulation is simulation used for project management training and analysis.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] It is often used as a training simulation for project managers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] In other cases, it is used for what-if analysis and for supporting decision-making in real projects.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Frequently the simulation is conducted using software tools.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] A robotics simulator is used to create embedded applications for a specific (or not) robot without being dependent on the 'real' robot.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] In some cases, these applications can be transferred to the real robot (or rebuilt) without modifications.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Robotics simulators allow reproducing situations that cannot be 'created' in the real world because of cost, time, or the 'uniqueness' of a resource.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] A simulator also allows fast robot prototyping.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Many robot simulators feature physics engines to simulate a robot's dynamics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Such simulations can help predict the impact of how improvements in methods might impact variability, cost, labor time, and the number of transactions at various stages in the process.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] A full-featured computerized process simulator can be used to depict such models, as can simpler educational demonstrations using spreadsheet software, pennies being transferred between cups based on the roll of a die, or dipping into a tub of colored beads with a scoop.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] In sports, computer simulations are often done to predict the outcome of events and the performance of individual sportspeople.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] They attempt to recreate the event through models built from statistics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The increase in technology has allowed anyone with knowledge of programming the ability to run simulations of their models.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The simulations are built from a series of mathematical algorithms, or models, and can vary with accuracy.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Accuscore, which is licensed by companies such as ESPN, is a well-known simulation program for all major sports.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] It offers a detailed analysis of games through simulated betting lines, projected point totals and overall probabilities.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] With the increased interest in fantasy sports simulation models that predict individual player performance have gained popularity.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Companies like What If Sports and StatFox specialize in not only using their simulations for predicting game results but how well individual players will do as well.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Many people use models to determine whom to start in their fantasy leagues.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Another way simulations are helping the sports field is in the use of biomechanics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Models are derived and simulations are run from data received from sensors attached to athletes and video equipment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Sports biomechanics aided by simulation models answer questions regarding training techniques such as the effect of fatigue on throwing performance (height of throw) and biomechanical factors of the upper limbs (reactive strength index; hand contact time).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Computer simulations allow their users to take models which before were too complex to run, and give them answers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulations have proven to be some of the best insights into both play performance and team predictability.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Simulation was used at Kennedy Space Center (KSC) to train and certify Space Shuttle engineers during simulated launch countdown operations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The Space Shuttle engineering community would participate in a launch countdown integrated simulation before each Shuttle flight.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] This simulation is a virtual simulation where real people interact with simulated Space Shuttle vehicle and Ground Support Equipment (GSE) hardware.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation, also known as S0044, involved countdown processes that would integrate many of the Space Shuttle vehicle and GSE systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Some of the Shuttle systems integrated in the simulation are the main propulsion system, RS-25, solid rocket boosters, ground liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen, external tank, flight controls, navigation, and avionics.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation took place at the Kennedy Space Center Launch Control Center firing rooms.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The firing room used during the simulation is the same control room where real launch countdown operations are executed.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] As a result, equipment used for real launch countdown operations is engaged.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The Space Shuttle vehicle hardware and related GSE hardware is simulated by mathematical models (written in Shuttle Ground Operations Simulator (SGOS) modeling language) that behave and react like real hardware.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] During the Shuttle Final Countdown Phase Simulation, engineers command and control hardware via real application software executing in the control consoles – just as if they were commanding real vehicle hardware.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] However, these real software applications do not interface with real Shuttle hardware during simulations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Instead, the applications interface with mathematical model representations of the vehicle and GSE hardware.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Consequently, the simulations bypass sensitive and even dangerous mechanisms while providing engineering measurements detailing how the hardware would have reacted.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Since these math models interact with the command and control application software, models and simulations are also used to debug and verify the functionality of application software.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The only true way to test GNSS receivers (commonly known as Sat-Nav's in the commercial world) is by using an RF Constellation Simulator.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] A receiver that may, for example, be used on an aircraft, can be tested under dynamic conditions without the need to take it on a real flight.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] The test conditions can be repeated exactly, and there is full control over all the test parameters. this is not possible in the 'real-world' using the actual signals.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] For testing receivers that will use the new Galileo (satellite navigation) there is no alternative, as the real signals do not yet exist.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Predicting weather conditions by extrapolating/interpolating previous data is one of the real use of simulation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Most of the weather forecasts use this information published by Weather bureaus.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] This kind of simulations helps in predicting and forewarning about extreme weather conditions like the path of an active hurricane/cyclone.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Numerical weather prediction for forecasting involves complicated numeric computer models to predict weather accurately by taking many parameters into account.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Strategy games—both traditional and modern—may be viewed as simulations of abstracted decision-making for the purpose of training military and political leaders (see History of Go for an example of such a tradition, or Kriegsspiel for a more recent example).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Many other video games are simulators of some kind.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] Such games can simulate various aspects of reality, from business, to government, to construction, to piloting vehicles (see above).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/simulation-p02] However, the connection between simulation and dissembling later faded out and is now only of linguistic interest.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software testing can provide objective, independent information about the quality of software and the risk of its failure to a user or sponsor or any other stakeholder.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software testing can determine the correctness of software for specific scenarios but cannot determine correctness for all scenarios.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Based on the criteria for measuring correctness from an oracle, software testing employs principles and mechanisms that might recognize a problem.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Examples of oracles include specifications, contracts, comparable products, past versions of the same product, inferences about intended or expected purpose, user or customer expectations, relevant standards, and applicable laws.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be functional or non-functional in nature.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often dynamic in nature: running the software to verify actual output matches expected.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] It can also be static in nature: reviewing code and its associated documentation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often used to answer the question: Does the software do what it is supposed to do and what it needs to do?
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Information learned from software testing may be used to improve the process by which software is developed.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] A commonly suggested approach to automated testing is the "test pyramid," wherein most of the tests are unit tests, followed by a smaller set of integration tests and finally a few end-to-end (e2e) tests.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] A study conducted by NIST in 2002 reported that software bugs cost the U.S. economy $59.5 billion annually.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] More than a third of this cost could be avoided if better software testing was performed.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Outsourcing software testing because of costs is very common, with China, the Philippines, India and Pakistan being preferred destinations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Myers initially introduced the separation of debugging from testing in 1979.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Although his attention was on breakage testing ("A successful test case is one that detects an as-yet undiscovered error."), it illustrated the desire of the software engineering community to separate fundamental development activities, such as debugging, from that of verification.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software testing typically includes handling software bugs – a defect in the code that causes an undesirable result.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Bugs generally slow testing progress and involve programmer assistance to debug and fix.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] For example, a defect in dead code will not be considered a failure.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] A defect that does not cause failure at one point in time may lead to failure later due to environmental changes.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Examples of environment change include running on new computer hardware, changes in data, and interacting with different software.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software testing is typically goal driven.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] A single defect may result in multiple failure symptoms.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software testing may involve a Requirements gap – omission from the design for a requirement.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Requirement gaps can often be non-functional requirements such as testability, scalability, maintainability, performance, and security.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] A fundamental limitation of software testing is that testing under *all* combinations of inputs and preconditions (initial state) is not feasible, even with a simple product.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Defects that manifest in unusual conditions are difficult to find in testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Also, non-functional dimensions of quality (how it is supposed to *be* versus what it is supposed to *do*) – usability, scalability, performance, compatibility, and reliability – can be subjective; something that constitutes sufficient value to one person may not to another.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Although testing for every possible input is not feasible, testing can use combinatorics to maximize coverage while minimizing tests.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Test automation is the use of software (separate from the software being tested) for controlling the execution of tests and comparing actual outcome with predicted.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Test automation supports testing the system under test (SUT) without manual interaction which can lead to faster test execution and testing more often.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Test automation is a key aspect of continuous testing and often for continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be categorized into levels based on how much of the software system is the focus of a test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Unit testing, a.k.a. component or module testing, is a form of software testing by which isolated source code is tested to validate expected behavior.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Integration testing is a form of software testing in which multiple software components, modules, or services are tested together to verify they work as expected when combined.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The focus is on testing the interactions and data exchange between integrated parts, rather than testing components in isolation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] System testing, a.k.a. end-to-end (E2E) testing, is testing conducted on a complete software system.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] There are many approaches to software testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Reviews, walkthroughs, or inspections are referred to as static testing, whereas executing programmed code with a given set of test cases is referred to as dynamic testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Static testing is often implicit, like proofreading, plus when programming tools/text editors check source code structure or compilers (precompilers) check syntax and data flow as static program analysis.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing takes place when the program itself is run.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing may begin before the program is 100% complete in order to test particular sections of code and are applied to discrete functions or modules.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Typical techniques for these are either using stubs/drivers or execution from a debugger environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Static testing involves verification, whereas dynamic testing also involves validation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Passive testing means verifying the system's behavior without any interaction with the software product.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Contrary to active testing, testers do not provide any test data but look at system logs and traces.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] They mine for patterns and specific behavior in order to make some kind of decisions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] This is related to offline runtime verification and log analysis.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Exploratory testing is an approach to software testing that is concisely described as simultaneous learning, test design and test execution.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software testing can often be divided into white-box and black-box.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] These two approaches are used to describe the point of view that the tester takes when designing test cases.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] A hybrid approach called grey-box that includes aspects of both boxes may also be applied to software testing methodology.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] White-box testing (also known as clear box testing, glass box testing, transparent box testing, and structural testing) verifies the internal structures or workings of a program, as opposed to the functionality exposed to the end-user.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] In white-box testing, an internal perspective of the system (the source code), as well as programming skills are used to design test cases.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The tester chooses inputs to exercise paths through the code and determines the appropriate outputs.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] This is analogous to testing nodes in a circuit, e.g., in-circuit testing (ICT).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] While white-box testing can be applied at the unit, integration, and system levels of the software testing process, it is usually done at the unit level.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] It can test paths within a unit, paths between units during integration, and between subsystems during a system–level test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Though this method of test design can uncover many errors or problems, it might not detect unimplemented parts of the specification or missing requirements.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Code coverage tools can evaluate the completeness of a test suite that was created with any method, including black-box testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] This allows the software team to examine parts of a system that are rarely tested and ensures that the most important function points have been tested.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] 100% statement coverage ensures that all code paths or branches (in terms of control flow) are executed at least once.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] This is helpful in ensuring correct functionality, but not sufficient since the same code may process different inputs correctly or incorrectly.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing (also known as functional testing) describes designing test cases without knowledge of the implementation, without reading the source code.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The testers are only aware of what the software is supposed to do, not how it does it.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing methods include: equivalence partitioning, boundary value analysis, all-pairs testing, state transition tables, decision table testing, fuzz testing, model-based testing, use case testing, exploratory testing, and specification-based testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing aims to test the functionality of software according to the applicable requirements.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] This level of testing usually requires thorough test cases to be provided to the tester, who then can simply verify that for a given input, the output value (or behavior), either "is" or "is not" the same as the expected value specified in the test case.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Test cases are built around specifications and requirements, i.e., what the application is supposed to do.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] It uses external descriptions of the software, including specifications, requirements, and designs, to derive test cases.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] These tests can be functional or non-functional, though usually functional.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing may be necessary to assure correct functionality, but it is insufficient to guard against complex or high-risk situations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Black box testing can be used to any level of testing although usually not at the unit level.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Component interface testing is a variation of black-box testing, with the focus on the data values beyond just the related actions of a subsystem component.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The practice of component interface testing can be used to check the handling of data passed between various units, or subsystem components, beyond full integration testing between those units.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The data being passed can be considered as "message packets" and the range or data types can be checked for data generated from one unit and tested for validity before being passed into another unit.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] One option for interface testing is to keep a separate log file of data items being passed, often with a timestamp logged to allow analysis of thousands of cases of data passed between units for days or weeks.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Tests can include checking the handling of some extreme data values while other interface variables are passed as normal values.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Unusual data values in an interface can help explain unexpected performance in the next unit.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The aim of visual testing is to provide developers with the ability to examine what was happening at the point of software failure by presenting the data in such a way that the developer can easily find the information he or she requires, and the information is expressed clearly.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] At the core of visual testing is the idea that showing someone a problem (or a test failure), rather than just describing it, greatly increases clarity and understanding.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Visual testing, therefore, requires the recording of the entire test process – capturing everything that occurs on the test system in video format.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Output videos are supplemented by real-time tester input via picture-in-a-picture webcam and audio commentary from microphones.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Visual testing provides a number of advantages.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The quality of communication is increased drastically because testers can show the problem (and the events leading up to it) to the developer as opposed to just describing it, and the need to replicate test failures will cease to exist in many cases.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The developer will have all the evidence he or she requires of a test failure and can instead focus on the cause of the fault and how it should be fixed.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Ad hoc testing and exploratory testing are important methodologies for checking software integrity because they require less preparation time to implement, while the important bugs can be found quickly.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] In ad hoc testing, where testing takes place in an improvised impromptu way, the ability of the tester(s) to base testing off documented methods and then improvise variations of those tests can result in a more rigorous examination of defect fixes.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] However, unless strict documentation of the procedures is maintained, one of the limits of ad hoc testing is lack of repeatability.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing (American spelling: gray-box testing) involves using knowledge of internal data structures and algorithms for purposes of designing tests while executing those tests at the user, or black-box level.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The tester will often have access to both "the source code and the executable binary." Grey-box testing may also include reverse engineering (using dynamic code analysis) to determine, for instance, boundary values or error messages.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Manipulating input data and formatting output do not qualify as grey-box, as the input and output are clearly outside of the "black box" that we are calling the system under test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] This distinction is particularly important when conducting integration testing between two modules of code written by two different developers, where only the interfaces are exposed for the test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] By knowing the underlying concepts of how the software works, the tester makes better-informed testing choices while testing the software from outside.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Typically, a grey-box tester will be permitted to set up an isolated testing environment with activities, such as seeding a database.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The tester can observe the state of the product being tested after performing certain actions such as executing SQL statements against the database and then executing queries to ensure that the expected changes have been reflected.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing implements intelligent test scenarios based on limited information.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] This will particularly apply to data type handling, exception handling, and so on.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] With the concept of grey-box testing, this "arbitrary distinction" between black- and white-box testing has faded somewhat.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Installation testing is a type of software testing that verifies that users can successfully install and set up software in its intended environments (e.g., operating systems, computer hardware).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Most software systems have installation procedures that are needed before they can be used for their main purpose.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Installation testing focuses on these procedures and whether they're sufficient for achieving an installed, usable software system.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Procedures of this kind may involve full or partial upgrades, and install/uninstall processes.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] For example, in the case of a lack of backward compatibility, this can occur because the programmers develop and test software only on the latest version of the target environment, which not all users may be running.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] This results in the unintended consequence that the latest work may not function on earlier versions of the target environment, or on older hardware that earlier versions of the target environment were capable of using.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Sometimes such issues can be fixed by proactively abstracting operating system functionality into a separate program module or library.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Sanity testing determines whether it is reasonable to proceed with further testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Smoke testing consists of minimal attempts to operate the software, designed to determine whether there are any basic problems that will prevent it from working at all.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Such tests can be used as build verification test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Regression testing focuses on finding defects after a major code change has occurred.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Specifically, it seeks to uncover software regressions, as degraded or lost features, including old bugs that have come back.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Such regressions occur whenever software functionality that was previously working correctly, stops working as intended.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Typically, regressions occur as an unintended consequence of program changes, when the newly developed part of the software collides with the previously existing code.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Common methods of regression testing include re-running previous sets of test cases and checking whether previously fixed faults have re-emerged.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The depth of testing depends on the phase in the release process and the risk of the added features.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] They can either be complete, for changes added late in the release or deemed to be risky, or be very shallow, consisting of positive tests on each feature, if the changes are early in the release or deemed to be of low risk.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing is system-level testing to ensure the software meets customer expectations.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing may be performed at the end or in the middle of a project, including after each completed user story in an agile project.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Tests are frequently grouped into these levels by where they are performed in the software development process, or by the level of specificity of the test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Sometimes, UAT is performed by the customer, in their environment and on their own hardware.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] OAT is used to conduct operational readiness (prerelease) of a product, service or system as part of a quality management system.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] OAT is a common type of non-functional software testing, used mainly in software development and software maintenance projects.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] This type of testing focuses on the operational readiness of the system to be supported, or to become part of the production environment.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Hence, it is also known as operational readiness testing (ORT) or operations readiness and assurance (OR&A) testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Functional testing within OAT is limited to those tests that are required to verify the *non-functional* aspects of the system.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] In addition, the software testing should ensure that the portability of the system, as well as working as expected, does not also damage or partially corrupt its operating environment or cause other processes within that environment to become inoperative.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Contractual acceptance testing is performed based on the contract's acceptance criteria defined during the agreement of the contract, while regulatory acceptance testing is performed based on the relevant regulations to the software product.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Both of these two tests can be performed by users or independent testers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Regulation acceptance testing sometimes involves the regulatory agencies auditing the test results.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is simulated or actual operational testing by potential users/customers or an independent test team at the developers' site.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is often employed for off-the-shelf software as a form of internal acceptance testing before the software goes to beta testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Beta testing comes after alpha testing and can be considered a form of external user acceptance testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Versions of the software, known as beta versions, are released to a limited audience outside of the programming team known as beta testers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The software is released to groups of people so that further testing can ensure the product has few faults or bugs.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Beta versions can be made available to the open public to increase the feedback field to a maximal number of future users and to deliver value earlier, for an extended or even indefinite period of time (perpetual beta).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Functional testing refers to activities that verify a specific action or function of the code.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] These are usually found in the code requirements documentation, although some development methodologies work from use cases or user stories.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Non-functional testing refers to aspects of the software that may not be related to a specific function or user action, such as scalability or other performance, behavior under certain constraints, or security.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Testing will determine the breaking point, the point at which extremes of scalability or performance leads to unstable execution.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Non-functional requirements tend to be those that reflect the quality of the product, particularly in the context of the suitability perspective of its users.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to obtain immediate feedback on the business risks associated with a software release candidate.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing includes the validation of both functional requirements and non-functional requirements; the scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Destructive testing attempts to cause the software or a sub-system to fail.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] It verifies whether the software functions properly when it receives invalid or unexpected inputs, thereby assessing the robustness of input validation and error-management routines.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software fault injection, in the form of fuzzing, is an example of failure testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Various commercial non-functional testing tools are linked from the software fault injection page; there are also numerous open-source and free software tools available that perform destructive testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Performance testing is generally executed to determine how a system or sub-system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] There is little agreement on what the specific goals of performance testing are.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The terms load testing, performance testing, scalability testing, and volume testing, are often used interchangeably.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Real-time software systems have strict timing constraints.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] To test if timing constraints are met, real-time testing is used.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Usability testing is to check if the user interface is easy to use and understand.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] It is concerned mainly with the use of the application.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] This is not a kind of testing that can be automated; actual human users are needed, being monitored by skilled UI designers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Usability testing can use structured models to check how well an interface works.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The Stanton, Theofanos, and Joshi (2015) model looks at user experience, and the Al-Sharafat and Qadoumi (2016) model is for expert evaluation, helping to assess usability in digital applications.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Accessibility testing is done to ensure that the software is accessible to persons with disabilities.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Security testing is essential for software that processes confidential data to prevent system intrusion by hackers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Testing for internationalization and localization validates that the software can be used with different languages and geographic regions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The process of pseudolocalization is used to test the ability of an application to be translated to another language, and make it easier to identify when the localization process may introduce new bugs into the product.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Globalization testing verifies that the software is adapted for a new culture, such as different currencies or time zones.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Actual translation to human languages must be tested, too.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Development testing is a software development process that involves the synchronized application of a broad spectrum of defect prevention and detection strategies in order to reduce software development risks, time, and costs.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] It is performed by the software developer or engineer during the construction phase of the software development lifecycle.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Development testing aims to eliminate construction errors before code is promoted to other testing; this strategy is intended to increase the quality of the resulting software as well as the efficiency of the overall development process.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Depending on the organization's expectations for software development, development testing might include static code analysis, data flow analysis, metrics analysis, peer code reviews, unit testing, code coverage analysis, traceability, and other software testing practices.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] A/B testing is a method of running a controlled experiment to determine if a proposed change is more effective than the current approach.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Customers are routed to either a current version (control) of a feature, or to a modified version (treatment) and data is collected to determine which version is better at achieving the desired outcome.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Concurrent or concurrency testing assesses the behaviour and performance of software and systems that use concurrent computing, generally under normal usage conditions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Typical problems this type of testing will expose are deadlocks, race conditions and problems with shared memory/resource handling.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] In software testing, conformance testing verifies that a product performs according to its specified standards.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Compilers, for instance, are extensively tested to determine whether they meet the recognized standard for that language.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] For example, every output from a serialization function should be accepted by the corresponding deserialization function, and every output from a sort function should be a monotonically increasing list containing exactly the same elements as its input.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Property testing libraries allow the user to control the strategy by which random inputs are constructed, to ensure coverage of degenerate cases, or inputs featuring specific patterns that are needed to fully exercise aspects of the implementation under test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Property testing is also sometimes known as "generative testing" or "QuickCheck testing" since it was introduced and popularized by the Haskell library QuickCheck.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Metamorphic testing (MT) is a property-based software testing technique, which can be an effective approach for addressing the test oracle problem and test case generation problem.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The test oracle problem is the difficulty of determining the expected outcomes of selected test cases or to determine whether the actual outputs agree with the expected outcomes.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] VCR testing, also known as "playback testing" or "record/replay" testing, is a testing technique for increasing the reliability and speed of regression tests that involve a component that is slow or unreliable to communicate with, often a third-party API outside of the tester's control.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] It involves making a recording ("cassette") of the system's interactions with the external component, and then replaying the recorded interactions as a substitute for communicating with the external system on subsequent runs of the test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The technique was popularized in web development by the Ruby library vcr.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] It is often used in the context of distributed systems, service-oriented software architectures, and microservices.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Since the early 2020s, artificial intelligence has increasingly been integrated into software testing workflows.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] AI-driven testing methods automate the creation of test cases, dynamically adapt to changes, and leverage machine learning to identify high-risk areas of the codebase — an approach that enhances regression testing efficiency while expanding overall test coverage.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] A key development is **self-healing test automation**, in which automated tests automatically detect and adapt to changes in a user interface without human intervention.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Studies of AI-driven test automation across over 3,600 grey literature sources identified self-healing test scripts as one of the most common AI solutions in practice.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] A case study presented at the 2023 International Conference on Information Management and Technology (ICIMTech) found that integrating shift-left testing into an agile development methodology over one year measurably reduced the number of bugs reaching production.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] In an organization, testers may be in a separate team from the rest of the software development team or they may be integrated into one team.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Software testing can also be performed by non-dedicated software testers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] In the 1980s, the term *software tester* started to be used to denote a separate profession.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Notable software testing roles and titles include: *test manager*, *test lead*, *test analyst*, *test designer*, *tester*, *automation developer*, and *test administrator*.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Organizations that develop software, perform testing differently, but there are common patterns.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] In waterfall development, testing is generally performed after the code is completed, but before the product is shipped to the customer.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] This practice often results in the testing phase being used as a project buffer to compensate for project delays, thereby compromising the time devoted to testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Some contend that the waterfall process allows for testing to start when the development project starts and to be a continuous process until the project finishes.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Agile software development commonly involves testing while the code is being written and organizing teams with both programmers and testers and with team members performing both programming and testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] One agile practice, test-driven software development (TDD), is a way of unit testing such that unit-level testing is performed while writing the product code.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Test code is updated as new features are added and failure conditions are discovered (bugs fixed).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Commonly, the unit test code is maintained with the project code, integrated in the build process, and run on each build and as part of regression testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Goals of this continuous integration is to support development and reduce defects.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] Even in organizations that separate teams by programming and testing functions, many often have the programmers perform unit testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The sample below is common for waterfall development.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p01] The same activities are commonly found in other development models, but might be described differently.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] The terms verification and validation are commonly used interchangeably in the industry; it is also common to see these two terms defined with contradictory definitions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Verification is the process of evaluating a system or component to determine whether the products of a given development phase satisfy the conditions imposed at the start of that phase.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Validation is the process of evaluating a system or component during or at the end of the development process to determine whether it satisfies specified requirements.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Verification is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that specified requirements have been fulfilled.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Validation is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that the requirements for a specific intended use or application have been fulfilled.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] The contradiction is caused by the use of the concepts of requirements and specified requirements but with different meanings.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] In the case of IEEE standards, the specified requirements, mentioned in the definition of validation, are the set of problems, needs and wants of the stakeholders that the software must solve and satisfy.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Such requirements are documented in a Software Requirements Specification (SRS).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] And, the products mentioned in the definition of verification, are the output artifacts of every phase of the software development process.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] These products are, in fact, specifications such as Architectural Design Specification, Detailed Design Specification, etc.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] The SRS is also a specification, but it cannot be verified (at least not in the sense used here – more on this subject below).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] But, for the ISO 9000, the specified requirements are the set of specifications, as just mentioned above, that must be verified.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A specification, as previously explained, is the product of a software development process phase that receives another specification as input.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A specification is verified successfully when it correctly implements its input specification.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] All the specifications can be verified except the SRS because it is the first one (it can be validated, though).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] An example scenario be that the Design Specification must implement the SRS, and the Construction phase artifacts must implement the Design Specification.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] So, when these words are defined in common terms, the apparent contradiction disappears.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Both the SRS and the software must be validated.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] The SRS can be validated statically by consulting with the stakeholders.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Nevertheless, running some partial implementation of the software or a prototype of any kind (dynamic testing) and obtaining positive feedback from them, can further increase the certainty that the SRS is correctly formulated.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] On the other hand, the software, as a final and running product (not its artifacts and documents, including the source code) must be validated dynamically with the stakeholders by executing the software and having them to try it.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Some might argue that, for SRS, the input is the words of stakeholders and, therefore, SRS validation is the same as SRS verification.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Thinking this way is not advisable as it only causes more confusion.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] It is better to think of verification as a process involving a formal and technical input document.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] In some organizations, software testing is part of a software quality assurance (SQA) process.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] In SQA, software process specialists and auditors are concerned with the software development process rather than just the artifacts such as documentation, code and systems.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] They examine and change the software engineering process itself to reduce the number of faults that end up in the delivered software: the so-called defect rate.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] What constitutes an acceptable defect rate depends on the nature of the software; a flight simulator video game would have much higher defect tolerance than software for an actual airplane.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Although there are close links with SQA, testing departments often exist independently, and there may be no SQA function in some companies.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Software testing is an activity to investigate software under test in order to provide quality-related information to stakeholders.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] By contrast, QA (quality assurance) is the implementation of policies and procedures intended to prevent defects from reaching customers.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Quality measures include such topics as correctness, completeness, security and ISO/IEC 9126 requirements such as capability, reliability, efficiency, portability, maintainability, compatibility, and usability.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] There are a number of frequently used software metrics, or measures, which are used to assist in determining the state of the software or the adequacy of the testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A software testing process can produce several artifacts.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] The actual artifacts produced are a factor of the software development model used, stakeholder and organisational needs.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A test plan is a document detailing the approach that will be taken for intended test activities.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] The plan may include aspects such as objectives, scope, processes and procedures, personnel requirements, and contingency plans.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] The test plan could come in the form of a single plan that includes all test types (like an acceptance or system test plan) and planning considerations, or it may be issued as a master test plan that provides an overview of more than one detailed test plan (a plan of a plan).
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A test plan can be, in some cases, part of a wide "test strategy" which documents overall testing approaches, which may itself be a master test plan or even a separate artifact.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] In software development, a traceability matrix (TM) is a document, usually in the form of a table, used to assist in determining the completeness of a relationship by correlating any two baselined documents using a many-to-many relationship comparison.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] It is often used with high-level requirements (these often consist of marketing requirements) and detailed requirements of the product to the matching parts of high-level design, detailed design, test plan, and test cases.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A test case normally consists of a unique identifier, requirement references from a design specification, preconditions, events, a series of steps (also known as actions) to follow, input, output, expected result, and the actual result.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Clinically defined, a test case is an input and an expected result.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] This can be as terse as "for condition x your derived result is y", although normally test cases describe in more detail the input scenario and what results might be expected.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] It can occasionally be a series of steps (but often steps are contained in a separate test procedure that can be exercised against multiple test cases, as a matter of economy) but with one expected result or expected outcome.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] The optional fields are a test case ID, test step, or order of execution number, related requirement(s), depth, test category, author, and check boxes for whether the test is automatable and has been automated.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Larger test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps, and descriptions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A test case should also contain a place for the actual result.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] These steps can be stored in a word processor document, spreadsheet, database, or other common repositories.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] In a database system, you may also be able to see past test results, who generated the results, and what system configuration was used to generate those results.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] These past results would usually be stored in a separate table.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A test script is a procedure or programming code that replicates user actions.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Initially, the term was derived from the product of work created by automated regression test tools.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A test case will be a baseline to create test scripts using a tool or a program.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] In software development, a test suite, less commonly known as a validation suite, is a collection of test cases that are intended to be used to test a software program to show that it has some specified set of behaviors.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A test suite often contains detailed instructions or goals for each collection of test cases and information on the system configuration to be used during testing.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A group of test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps and descriptions of the following tests.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] In most cases, multiple sets of values or data are used to test the same functionality of a particular feature.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] All the test values and changeable environmental components are collected in separate files and stored as test data.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] It is also useful to provide this data to the client and with the product or a project.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] There are techniques to generate Test data.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] The software, tools, samples of data input and output, and configurations are all referred to collectively as a test harness.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A test run is a collection of test cases or test suites that the user is executing and comparing the expected with the actual results.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Once complete, a report or all executed tests may be generated.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Several certification programs exist to support the professional aspirations of software testers and quality assurance specialists.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] A few practitioners argue that the testing field is not ready for certification, as mentioned in the controversy section.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] is so expensive relative to its value that it should be used sparingly.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] The test automation then can be considered as a way to capture and implement the requirements.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] As a general rule, the larger the system and the greater the complexity, the greater the ROI in test automation.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Also, the investment in tools and expertise can be amortized over multiple projects with the right level of knowledge sharing within an organization.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Significant opposition has formed out of the ranks of the context-driven school of software testing about the ISO 29119 standard.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Professional testing associations, such as the International Society for Software Testing, have attempted to have the standard withdrawn.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] No certification now offered actually requires the applicant to show their ability to test software.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] No certification is based on a widely accepted body of knowledge.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] Certification itself cannot measure an individual's productivity, their skill, or practical knowledge, and cannot guarantee their competence, or professionalism as a tester.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/software-testing-p02] There are opposing views on the applicability of studies used to show the relative expense of fixing defects depending on their introduction and detection.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/system-under-test] From a unit testing perspective, the system under test represents all of the classes in a test that are not predefined pieces of code like stubs or even mocks.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/system-under-test] Each one of this can have its own configuration (a name and a version), making it scalable for a series of tests to get more and more precise, according to the quantity of quality of the system in test.
[src:hardware-in-the-loop/system-under-test] ISO/IEC/IEEE 29119 defines SUT within a standardized vocabulary and test-process framework.
